"Peterson A.T., Ortega-Huerta M.A., Bartley J., Sánchez-Cordero V., Soberón J., Buddemeler R.H., Stockwell D.R.B.","Future projections for Mexican faunas under global climate change scenarios",2002,"Nature","416","6881",,"626","629",,,10.1038/416626a,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0037061522&partnerID=40&md5=aa3a9e373e30c5a57c4c6684657bc6f4","Natural History Museum, The University of Kansas, Lawrence, KS 66045, United States","Peterson, A.T., Natural History Museum, The University of Kansas, Lawrence, KS 66045, United States; Ortega-Huerta, M.A., Natural History Museum, The University of Kansas, Lawrence, KS 66045, United States; Bartley, J., Natural History Museum, The University of Kansas, Lawrence, KS 66045, United States; Sánchez-Cordero, V., Natural History Museum, The University of Kansas, Lawrence, KS 66045, United States; Soberón, J., Natural History Museum, The University of Kansas, Lawrence, KS 66045, United States; Buddemeler, R.H., Natural History Museum, The University of Kansas, Lawrence, KS 66045, United States; Stockwell, D.R.B., Natural History Museum, The University of Kansas, Lawrence, KS 66045, United States","Global climates are changing rapidly, with unexpected consequences. Because elements of biodiversity respond intimately to climate as an important driving force of distributional limitation, distributional shifts and biodiversity lossess are expected. Nevertheless, in spite of modelling efforts focused on single species or entire ecosystems, a few preliminary surveys of fauna-wide effects, and evidence of climate change-mediated shifts in several species, the likely effects of climate change on species' distributions remain little known, and fauna-wide or community-level effects are almost completely unexplored. Here, using a genetic algorithm and museum specimen occurrence data, we develop ecological niche models for 1,870 species occurring in Mexico and project them onto two climate surfaces modelled for 2055. Although extinctions and drastic range reductions are predicted to be relatively few, species turnover in some local communities is predicted to be high (>40% of species), suggesting that severe ecological perturbations may result.",,"Biodiversity; Ecosystems; Genetic algorithms; Global climate; Climate change; biodiversity; climate change; fauna; global change; niche; article; biodiversity; climate change; community; controlled study; ecological niche; ecosystem; fauna; genetic algorithm; geographic distribution; geographical variation (species); global climate; Mexico; priority journal; sampling; species distribution; Algorithms; Animals; Birds; Butterflies; Climate; Computer Simulation; Ecosystem; Mammals; Mexico; Models, Biological; Population Dynamics; Species Specificity; Mexico",,,,,,"Houghton, J.T., (2001) IPCC Third Assessment Report: Climate Change, , (Cambridge Univ. Press, Cambridge, 2001); Johnston, K.M., Schmitz, O.J., Wildlife and climate change: Assessing the sensitivity of selected species to simulated doubling of atmospheric CO2 Glob (1997) Change Biol, 3, pp. 531-544; Dobson, A., Jolly, A., Rubenstein, D., The greenhouse effect and biological diversity (1989) Trends Ecol. Evol, 4, pp. 64-68; Chapin, F.S.I., Consequences of changing biodiversity (2000) Nature, 405, pp. 234-242; Woodward, F.I., Lomas, M.R., Betts, R.A., Vegetation-climate feedback in a greenhouse world (1998) Phil. Trans. R. Soc. Lond. B, 353, pp. 29-39; Sala, O.E., Global biodiversity scenarios for the year 2100 (2000) Science, 287, pp. 1770-1773; Price, J., Modeling the potential impacts of climate change on the summer distributions of Massachusetts passerines (2000) Birds Obs, 28, pp. 224-230; Visser, M.E., van Noordwijk, A.J., Tinbergen, J.M., Lessells, C.M., Warmer springs lead to mistimed reproduction in great tits (Parus major) (1998) Proc. R. Soc. Lond. B, 265, pp. 1867-1870; Parmesan, C., Climate and species' range (1996) Nature, 382, pp. 765-766; Soberon, J., Linking biodiversity information sources (1999) Trends Ecol. Evol, 14, p. 291; Peterson, A.T., Effects of global climate change on geographic distributions of Mexican Cracidae (2001) Ecol. Model, 144, pp. 21-30; Peterson, A.T., Predicting species' geographic distribution based on ecological niche modeling (2001) Condor, 103, pp. 599-605; Koopowitz, H., Thornhill, A.D., Andersen, M., A general stochastic model for the prediction of biodiversity losses based on habitat conversion (1994) Conserv. Biol, 8, pp. 438-452; Davis, A.J., Jenkinson, L.S., Lawton, J.H., Shorrocks, B., Wood, S., Making mistakes when predicting shifts in species range in response to global warming (1998) Nature, 391, pp. 783-786; Peterson, A.T., Vieglais, D.A., Predicting species invasions using ecological niche modeling (2001) BioScience, 51, pp. 363-371; Sánchez-Cordero, V., Martínez-Meyer, E., Museum specimen data predict crop damage by tropical rodents (2000) Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. USA, 97, pp. 7074-7077; Peterson, A.T., Stockwell, D.R.B., Kluza, D.A., Predicting Species Occurrences: Issues of Scale and Accuracy, , (ed. Scott, J.M.) (Island, Washington DC, in the press); Stockwell, D.R.B., Peters, D.P., The GARP modelling system: Problems and solutions to automated spatial prediction (1999) Int. J. Geograph. Inform. Systems, 13, pp. 143-158; Peterson, A.T., Navarro-Sigüenza, A.G., Alternate species concepts as bases for determining priority conservation areas (1999) Conserv. Biol, 13, pp. 427-431; Peterson, A.T., Navarro-Sigüenza, A.G., Benítez-Diaz, H., The need for continued scientific collecting: A geographic analysis of Mexican bird specimens (1998) Ibis, 140, pp. 288-294; Peterson, A.T., Soberón, J., Sánchez-Cordero, V., Conservatism of ecological niches in evolutionary time (1999) Science, 285, pp. 1265-1267; Llorente-Bousquets, J., Luis, A., Vargas, I., Papilionidae y Pieridae de México: Distribucíon Geográfica e Ilustración (1997), (Universidad Nacional Autónoma de México, Mexico City)Tobler, W.R., Smoot